                                                                Operation and Maintenance, Air Force
                                                                  Budget Activity: Operating Forces
                                                      Detail by Subactivity Group: Contractor Logistics Support
                                                                           ($ In Thousands)

I. Description of Operations Financed:
The funding in Subactivity Group 11W is for Contractor Logistics Support (CLS), Sustaining Engineering (SE) and the Technical Orders (TO) portion of the Weapon
System Sustainment (WSS) and resides in the centrally managed portfolio. CLS provides various functions such as depot level maintenance, repair, materiel
management, supply and repair parts management, and technical data management. SE resolves technical or supportability deficiencies while the TOs ensure up-to-date
technical data for sustainment in fielded weapon systems.


II. Force Structure Summary:
The funding in this Subactivity Group, supports CLS, SE, and TO requirements enabling the readiness of the Air Force's weapon systems. These assets are categorized
as Combat Air Forces, Helo Operations, Mobility Air Forces, Nuclear Deterrence, Formal and Readiness Training. Collectively, they provide the United States all the core
missions of Air Power to produce the effects of Global Vigilance, Global Reach, and Global Power.

The WSS requirements are developed through the Logistics Requirements Determination Process (LRDP) based on operational needs. The LRDP consists of three basic
phases: (1) develop requirements, (2) review, collaborate and validate requirements, (3) certify, prioritize and publish requirements. The entire process is managed by the
System Program Managers (SPM) and Program Group Managers (PGM), in the web-based tool named Sustainment Planning, Execution, and Reporting System
(SPERS).

All the remaining three WSS sustainment areas (CLS, SE & TO) have individual commodities with their own tailored sub-process specific to aircraft, engines, missiles,
other major end items and software. The lead Major Commands have the overall responsibility for the category of weapon systems. They provide the capability to the Joint
Force based on the current and projected demand for each individual weapon system.




