3) Mobility Air Forces ................................................................................................................................................................................ $326,194
The Mobility Air Forces (MAF) flying hour program is the foundational enabler of global power projection, providing the United States
with the strategic reach necessary to support integrated deterrence for Combat Forces. To build a resilient Joint Force prepared for
strategic competition, increased funding is essential, particularly as the costs of fuel, parts, and complex sustainment continue to
escalate. These flight hours are critical for mastering large-scale force employment and long-range precision strikes, which are vital
for effective campaigning against pacing challenges. Without sufficient funding to meet these demands, pilot proficiency will decline,
the combat radius of air and naval assets will be severely limited, and the ability to sustain the force will degrade, thereby curtailing
strategic options in a global crisis.

A ready and capable tanker fleet underpins the credibility of the entire Joint Force, directly addressing the National Defense
Strategy's priority of deterring aggression, particularly in the Indo-Pacific. By ensuring aircrews are proficient in complex, contested
environments, the U.S. demonstrates a strategic reach that complicates adversary planning and strengthens the assurance of our
allies. This makes MAF readiness inseparably linked to the readiness of the entire Joint Force.

Funding prioritizes the flying of our modern tanker fleet through the continued fielding of the KC-46A Pegasus while reinforcing the
legacy KC-135R/T fleet. With enhanced capabilities in refueling, the KC-46A represents a significant leap forward in supporting
operations within a contested environment. The combination of a modernized fleet and highly trained aircrews ensures the endurance
required for any Joint Force package.

Ultimately, this investment enhances the agility, lethality, and sustainment of the force. By enabling the rapid deployment and
sustained employment of combat power, the MAF flying hour program is a critical element of deterrence, allowing the Joint Force to
respond to crises with the speed, flexibility, and decisiveness required in a complex global security environment.

