INSERT INTO public.om_activity_years (activity_code, fiscal_year, service, appropriation, ba, sag_short_code, title, prior_year_actual, current_year_enacted, request_amount, fydp_yr1, fydp_yr2, fydp_yr3, fydp_yr4, narrative, content_hash, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$OM_NAVY_X_006$$, 2026, $$Navy$$, $$OM_NAVY$$, NULL, NULL, $$Table of Contents$$, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, $$ 4A4G Administration ............................................................................................................................................................................... 50




                                                                                                                                                                                                 Table of Contents
                                                                                                                                                                                                     (Page 1 of 1)
                                                                                                           3
THIS PAGE INTENTIONALLY LEFT BLANK
                                                         DEPARTMENT OF THE NAVY
                                                         APPROPRIATION HIGHLIGHTS
                                             OPERATION AND MAINTENANCE, MARINE CORPS RESERVE
                                                                ($ in Millions)

                                              Operations and Maintenance, Marine Corps Reserve (OMMCR)
                  FY 2024               Price              Program              FY 2025             Price           Program           FY 2026
                   Actuals             Growth              Growth               Enacted            Growth           Growth            Estimate
                    320.7                8.5                 5.1                 334.3              10.4              17.4             362.0

The Operation and Maintenance, Marine Corps Reserve (OMMCR) appropriation finances the day-to-day costs of operating the Marine Corps Forces Reserve
(MARFORRES), its functional activities and facilities. The Reserve Component is trained, organized, and equipped in the same manner as the active force and
provides augmentation, reinforcement, and relief to the active component to both mitigate risk and maximize opportunities; and is fundamental to the Marine
Corps’ Total Force concept. The FY 2026 President’s budget request sustains a force of 33,600 Reserve Marines assigned to units across the country. Like the
active component, the Marine Forces Reserve consists of the Marine Forces Reserve headquarters and its subordinate Marine Division, Marine Aircraft Wing,
and Marine Logistics Group, all of which are headquartered in New Orleans, Louisiana. The Reserve component is unique in that the subordinate
regiments/groups, battalions/squadrons, and companies/detachments are located at 158 reserve training centers and sites across the United States.

The FY 2026 estimate of $362 million includes a price increase of $10.4 million and a program increase of $17.4 million. Appropriation funds facility
sustainment at 53 percent of the OSD model reflecting the continuation of the Facilities Investment Optimization strategy, the Marine Corps’ initiative for a
holistic Facilities, Sustainment, Restoration and Modernization (FSRM) model; and supports ground depot maintenance active and reserve at 79.1 percent of the
total force requirement with the consolidated discretionary and mandatory budgets.

Implementing the President’s ‘Department of Government Efficiency’ Cost Efficiency Initiative, resulted in reductions of $3.5M to contract services, travel, and
workforce optimization in the Base Budget. These alternatives reduced the DOD components budgets to support the Administration’s priorities.

                                                          Budget Activity 01: Operating Forces
                     FY 2024           Price           Program         FY 2025         Price                 Program             FY 2026
                      Actuals         Growth           Growth         Enacted         Growth                 Growth              Estimate
                       309.6            8.1              3.9            321.6           10.3                  -19.6               312.3

Funding in this budget activity supports the Reserve Forces operations and maintenance requirements, materiel readiness, purchase and replacement of expense
type items authorized by unit training allowances, local repair of equipment, training centers, and embarkation materials for training and preparation for
mobilization. Funding also supports annual exercise and training participation to prepare individuals and units for deployments and provides resources for
equipment and ammunition shipments, essential travel, contract billeting, maintenance contact teams, inspections, reserve health assessments, contractor
engineering technical services, equipment calibration, global command and control system technicians, consumables, and equipment replacement/replenishment.
Additionally, this budget activity supports base operations support and facility sustainment, restoration, and modernization requirements.

The FY 2026 budget estimate of $312.3 million represents a decrease of $9.3 million from the FY 2025 enacted funding levels. This reduction includes $10.3
million attributed to price growth and -$19.6 million in program growth.




                                                                                                                       Exhibit PBA-19 Appropriation Highlights
                                                                                5
                                                                                                                                                  (Page 1 of 2)
                                                         DEPARTMENT OF THE NAVY
                                                         APPROPRIATION HIGHLIGHTS
                                             OPERATION AND MAINTENANCE, MARINE CORPS RESERVE
                                                                ($ in Millions)

The Operating Forces’ budget request includes an overall decrease of $13.2 million. Appropriation decrease reflects the Marine Forces Reserve right-sizing
of contractor support for implementing storage and optimization procedures to maintain adequate storage facilities for Class II life cycle equipment within
the framework of the Consolidated Storage Program (CSP).

The Depot Maintenance budget requests include an overall increase of $0.6 million. Appropriation increase provides for maintenance and overhaul of the
Missiles commodity equipment sets and weapon systems including the guided missile battery control central.

Sustainment, Restoration, and Modernization (FSRM); and Base Operating Support’s budget requests includes an overall average decrease of $3.5 million.
Appropriation decreases reflect reduced maintenance requirements of electronic and communication systems mobile complexes, test systems, and armored
refueler trailers, facilities sustainment, and installation support requirements respectively.


                                               Budget Activity 4: Administration and Service-Wide Activities
                     FY 2024           Price          Program          FY 2025          Price          Program                   FY 2026
                      Actuals         Growth           Growth          Enacted         Growth          Growth                    Estimate
                       11.1             0.3              1.2             12.7            0.2              36.9                     49.8


Funding in this budget activity provides administrative and logistical support to the Reserve Component. Funding provides supplies and materials for daily
operations and equipment purchases as well as civilian personnel, Selected Marine Corps Reserve (SMCR), Inactive Ready Reserve (IRR), and Individual
Marine Augments (IMA) support. These resources also support service from Defense Finance and Accounting Service (DFAS), Defense Information Systems
Agency (DISA) and Technology Service Organization (TSO).

The FY 2026 budget request of $49.8 million depicts a total increase of $37.1 million from the FY 2025 requested funding levels, of which $0.2 million is
attributed to inflation growth and $36.9 million in program growth. This increase supports backpay and benefits for the 1,679 service members eligible for
reinstatement under the military's COVID-19 vaccination mandate in accordance with Executive Order (EO) 14184.

                                                                     Strategic Readiness
                     FY 2024           Price           Program           FY 2025          Price              Program             FY 2026
